CrowdStrike's FQ2'26 saw YoY subscription growth tick down one last time to 20.1% before it laps the effects of its outage in July of last year, and starts to see lapping of easy comps and effects of customer satisfaction roll off in H2. With that said, while the company beat their guide by ~$21MM in the quarter (+1.8%), they raised full year by just $3MM and emphasized the guide anticipated professional services would be strong - implicitly this guided down subscription revenue in H2. This result is guidance a bit underwhelming vs. consensus, with Q3 guided ~$15MM (midpoint) below consensus and implied Q4 (midpoint) at ~$9MM below consensus.

**Platform growth remains a bright spot while the traditional business continues to** **decelerate.** ARR for Cloud Security + Identity Security + Next-Gen SIEM grew >40% YoY,and implicitly this meant the remaining business ARR decelerated to just higher than 10%YoY growth (down from just under 15% two quarters ago, and roughly 20% a year and year and a half ago). Added to this, the company showed off the accelerating contribution from their new flex license model, that grew by mode than ¼ QoQ, and reached 1000+ customers at an average ARR of $1MM+, implying flex deals account for more than 20% of ARR.

**Next-Gen Identity and LogScale SIEM redoubled focus delivers early results.** While their identity platform component had decelerated (and barely even grown in contribution half over half in FQ4'25), the company demonstrated their commitment to the category with the roll-out of a new offering, and showed off initial tradition with incremental H1 ARR added of $65MM (vs. $20MM in the prior six-month period). And coincident with earnings they announced an acquisition of Onum (private), another building block for a full real-time SIEM stack.

We tweak our model to reflect the latest Q2 numbers, but largely keep incremental growth similar to our prior model. Using a 50/50 "rule of 40"-based multiples regression (15x down from 18xwith outlier "halo" status), and our DCF (10% WACC, 3% growth) we update our 1-year PTO $343 and maintain our Market-Perform rating.

The company expects their business will accelerate with Red Canary partnership. On the partnership with Zscaler and Red Canary, Red Canary already had an existing partnership with CrowdStrike, providing managed services on top of CrowdStrike's technology to their customers. With Red Canary, they are transitioning more customers onto CrowdStrike technology while layering their services on Zscaler's capabilities. Management expects their business to accelerate due to this partnership, anticipating new deployments since prior to the partnership, deployment was not fully complete. They foresee growth in the percentage of deployed accounts over time.

Customer Commit Program effects will lap... but not all in H2. These were the "make it right" funds and discounts offered to customers after the outage. Management noted that some CCP dollars are spread over multiple years, so not all impact will be seen by the end of this FY.

Professional services revenue was significant this quarter but can be volatile - a broader range of contribution is contemplated in their updated guidance. The strength is influenced by factors sometimes beyond the company's control. This revenue typically arises when another vendor's technology fails to prevent a breach, and CrowdStrike steps in to remediate and replace that technology. Based on the recent strength, they are increasing the expected contribution range for professional services in the rest- of- year guidance.

Management believes both secure web browsers and endpoint agents are essential for the future. The company has its own browser extension integrated with their agents, a capability they have maintained for a long time. This integration was a key reason they chose not to acquire Talon, despite being an early investor. Palo Alto acquired the company in 2023.

Onum deal has not closed, thus guidance does not include any impacts. Management emphasized the deal is still pending, so business expectations and results discussed this quarter did not include any contribution for the acquisition.
EXHIBIT 1: Next- Gen SIEM is growing ARR fastest, contributing to overall ARR growth.
Source: Company reports, Bernstein analysis

EXHIBIT 2: We expect CRWD's ARR YoY growth rate to dip into the low \(20\%\) range before recovering to high- \(20\%\) by the end of FY26 (on the back of easy comps) before starting to decelerate again back into the mid- \(20\%\) by the end of FY27.
Source: Company reports, Bernstein estimates and analysis

EXHIBIT 3: NRR continued its dip mostly due to the outage impacts. We estimate this is the bottom for NRR and over coming quarters it will slowly pick up as the outage impacts wears off at the second half of FY2026.

Our price target of \(\) 343\(is an average of DCF (10% WACC, 3% terminal growth) and\) \sim 15x P / Sales (Next 5 - 8Q) \(comp multiple. P / Sales (Next 5 - 8Q) comp multiple is selected in the\) >10\% \(OpM Cloud SaaS cohort from our valuation framework analysis. We assume the current Cloud SaaS multiples regression line remains consistent for\) 1+year.

Downside risks beyond the macroeconomic risks include: continued tie to cloud growth, execution risk in going downmarket to target SMB customers; maintaining traction in the product portfolio outside their core endpoint business, platforms moving into their core business, premium price while established competitors are entering from SMB with more cost- effective offers, high valuation.

Upside risks include stronger than expected ARR re- acceleration in H2 on new and existing products, improved margin expansion, tailwind (not headwind) impact from DOGE/US Federal, strong adoption and low friction scaling from its Flex program, and weakening of the competitive environment.
